The protocol you described seems to avoid deadlocks and starvation, as it ensures that resources are acquired in a Control Sequential Manner (CSM) and philosophers who fail to acquire both chopsticks go back to the end of the queue. However, there might be a potential issue with fairness. If a philosopher frequently fails to acquire both chopsticks, they will keep going back to the end of the queue, making it less likely for them to eat.

A better protocol is the resource hierarchy solution. The idea is to assign an order or rank to the chopsticks and make the philosopher pick up the chopstick with lower rank first, then pick the higher-ranked chopstick. This way, when a philosopher cannot pick up both chopsticks, they will release the lower-ranked chopstick, avoiding the circular wait condition that leads to deadlock.

Here's a simple implementation for your solution:

```java
class Philosopher extends Thread {
    private static Semaphore[] chopsticks;
    private static LinkedList<Philosopher> queue = new LinkedList<>();

    public Philosopher(int i) {
        setId(i);
    }

    public void run() {
        while (true) {
            think();

            synchronized (queue) {
                queue.addLast(this);
            }

            boolean hasEaten = false;
            while (!hasEaten) {
                synchronized (queue) {
                    if (queue.getFirst() == this) {
                        if (chopsticks[getLeft()].tryAcquire()) {
                            if (chopsticks[getRight()].tryAcquire()) {
                                eat();
                                hasEaten = true;

                                chopsticks[getRight()].release();
                            }

                            chopsticks[getLeft()].release();

                            if (!hasEaten) {
                                queue.removeFirst();
                                queue.addLast(this);
                            } else {
                                queue.removeFirst();
                            }
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

And here's a simple implementation for the resource hierarchy solution:

```java
class BetterPhilosopher extends Thread {
    private final int id;
    private final Semaphore leftChopstick;
    private final Semaphore rightChopstick;

    public BetterPhilosopher(int id, Semaphore leftChopstick, Semaphore rightChopstick) {
        this.id = id;
        this.leftChopstick = leftChopstick;
        this.rightChopstick = rightChopstick;
    }

    public void run() {
        while (true) {
            think();
            pickUp(id, leftChopstick, rightChopstick);
            eat();
            putDown(leftChopstick, rightChopstick);
        }
    }

    private void pickUp(int id, Semaphore leftChopstick, Semaphore rightChopstick) {
        if (id % 2 == 0) {
            leftChopstick.acquireUninterruptibly();
            rightChopstick.acquireUninterruptibly();
        } else {
            rightChopstick.acquireUninterruptibly();
            leftChopstick.acquireUninterruptibly();
        }
    }

    private void putDown(Semaphore leftChopstick, Semaphore rightChopstick) {
        leftChopstick.release();
        rightChopstick.release();
    }
}
